40|$|This study {{examines}} {{the effect of}} air quality and administrative policies on use of urban trails in Indianapolis, IN. Attention is focused on two policy variables: (1) issuance of air pollution advisories and (2) the adoption of <b>Daylight</b> <b>Savings</b> <b>Time.</b> Results suggest that while trail use varies with air quality, current public advisories regarding air pollution may be of limited effectiveness in reducing trail users’ exposures to hazardous pollutants. In contrast, the adoption of <b>Daylight</b> <b>Savings</b> <b>Time</b> {{was associated with a}} statistically significant increase in traffic levels...|$|R
